{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XJEmPBAWiv1KPXsmr3Uon2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the key questions framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about a single transformation — query string → embedding vector → check dimension. Could be a unit test if we mock the embedding model, but the dimensionality check depends on what the real embedding model actually returns.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network required if we stub the embedding API.\n- LLM-DEP: The embedding model is an AI/ML model. Does correctness depend on what the real model produces? The assertion is `len(vector) == expected_dim`. \n\nActually, I need to think about this differently. The dimensionality of an embedding is determined by the model configuration itself — it's not something that varies based on the model's reasoning or intelligence. Any call to the real embedding API will consistently return vectors of the same dimension, regardless of input. So stubbing the model to return the correct dimension doesn't actually test anything meaningful; the real failure mode would be misconfiguration like using the wrong model endpoint or version. This means I do need the real embedding model to catch those kinds of errors, making this Agentic. The real issue is that mocking would hide configuration errors—if the wrong embedding model is set up, a stub returning the correct dimension would still pass. Since dimensionality is deterministic per model, I need to call the actual embedding API to catch misconfigurations. Per the rules, any execution path through a real AI/ML API defaults to Agentic, so I'm classifying this as Agentic, though Integration or System could work too.\n\nFor the similarity search ordering, the vector math itself is deterministic and doesn't involve an LLM, so it's really about whether the vector database is wired up correctly. I could test this with an in-process fake or local vector store, making it Integration, but if I use a real vector database instance, it becomes System.\n\nThe key question is where the failure mode lives—is it in how the database returns results, or in how my code interprets and preserves that ordering? Since similarity ordering is fundamental to vector databases and the issue could stem from query formation or database configuration, I think Integration is the minimum viable test level, though System is also reasonable.\n\nFor the LLM re-ranking behavior, this is clearly Agentic since it depends on the LLM actually changing the order based on nuanced intent—a mock would never catch that. And for the empty result set behavior, I need the real vector database to properly evaluate similarity thresholds and distinguish between \"close enough\" and \"not close enough,\" so that's REAL-INFRA territory.\n\nThe key failure mode I'm looking for is when a query with no genuinely close matches still returns low-relevance noise instead of an empty set. To test this meaningfully, I'd need a query that's actually far from all stored vectors and an embedding model that reflects that distance. An in-process fake vector DB with controlled similarity scores could work at the Integration level, but to verify the threshold behavior is actually meaningful rather than just passing through a pre-configured value, I'd probably need the real embedding model involved.\n\nActually, I'm conflating two things here. The behavior is about what the service does when it receives low-similarity results—that's deterministic threshold logic I can test with a stub returning low scores. The real risk is whether my threshold is calibrated correctly or whether the embedding model creates embeddings that never get far enough from database vectors. But since the behavior itself is about the system's response to low scores, not about the embedding quality, I can test this at Integration with a fake DB that returns controlled similarity scores.\n\nFor latency though, this is different—measuring end-to-end latency from query to ranked results requires real infrastructure. I need actual HTTP calls, real embedding API, real vector DB, and real LLM re-ranking. This is System level at minimum because the latency depends on real network and service performance, not just my code's logic. seconds) is deterministic.\n- But we do need the full pipeline including real LLM calls to measure accurate latency.\n\nI'd say Agentic is the minimum here because the pipeline includes real LLM calls, and measuring latency without real model calls would give meaningless results. The latency of the real LLM response is critical to the measurement.\n\nActually, per REAL-INFRA: \"could an in-process fake reproduce the exact failure?\" - No, because fake latency doesn't match real latency. This points to System at minimum. But since the pipeline also involves LLM calls, Agentic seems right.\n\nLet me reconsider - System level handles \"real HTTP, real external API calls\". The embedding model and LLM re-ranking are real external API calls. For latency testing, we need real API calls. This is either System (real HTTP) or Agentic.\n\nThe execution path goes through real AI/ML API calls, which per the guidelines means I should default to Agentic even though the assertion itself is deterministic. I'm considering whether this could be Workflow since there are multiple sequential steps—embedding, similarity search, then LLM re-ranking—but that pattern really applies to full agent pipelines. The core question is whether real LLM calls are needed, and they are, so Agentic is the right level for behavior 5.\n\nNow looking at my full classification, let me double-check behavior 1. The embedding dimensionality is entirely determined by which model is configured—text-embedding-ada-002 always returns 1536 dimensions, no variation. This isn't actually testing the model's behavior; it's testing configuration. I could verify this with a fake embedding that returns the expected dimension count, so maybe this should be Integration instead of Agentic.\n\nBut wait—the LLM-DEP rule says if the execution path passes through a real AI/ML API call, default to Agentic. This test does make that real call, and the only way to catch a misconfigured model is through that actual API. Even though the assertion itself is deterministic, I can't disqualify it from Agentic because the behavior depends on the model's output, not just infrastructure around it.\n\nFor behavior 2, I'm checking the integration criteria—there's no real network call needed if the vector DB is in-memory, no AI/ML output being tested, and no orchestration across multiple agentic stages. This one qualifies as Integration since the failure mode is purely about how the code queries and maintains ordering in the vector DB.\n\nFor behavior 4, the threshold decision is just cosine similarity math, not dependent on the LLM itself. I can use controlled fake similarity scores below the threshold to test the no-match response without needing a real embedding. This also fits Integration.\n\nI'm satisfied with these classifications now.\n\nNow I'm working through the probability distributions for each behavior. For embedding dimensionality, Unit testing wouldn't catch a misconfiguration, Integration could test model selection but not real dimensionality, System testing with a real HTTP call to the embedding API is sufficient since dimension is deterministic, and Agentic testing through the actual AI/ML execution path is most appropriate. I'm assigning probabilities accordingly, with Agentic getting the highest weight at 0.60.\n\nFor similarity search ordering, Integration testing with a local vector DB or fake data with controlled scores is the sweet spot at 0.65, since I can verify the ordering logic without needing a real service. System testing with a real vector DB would work but is less necessary. For LLM re-ranking, this is clearly Agentic territory at 0.85 since it requires actual LLM decision-making. And for empty results with no matches, Integration testing with controlled fake scores to verify threshold behavior gets the highest probability at 0.65, with Unit testing also viable at 0.15 for testing the threshold logic in isolation.\n\nNow looking at latency testing—end-to-end latency is fundamentally an Agentic concern at 0.65 since it involves real AI/ML calls in the pipeline, with System testing at 0.22 for real HTTP calls and Workflow at 0.10 for the full pipeline.\n\nI'm reconsidering behavior 2 on similarity ordering. The key insight is that the test needs the vector DB wired to the search service, which is an integration boundary. Unit testing would only cover a sort function in isolation, but the actual behavior is about the DB returning ordered results, so Integration is the minimum viable level.\n\nFor behavior 4, I need to think through the failure mode carefully. The service applies a similarity threshold and filters out low-score results. This threshold filtering logic can be tested with controlled stub similarity scores—the Integration level with a stub vector DB returning low scores is sufficient to verify the empty result set. The critical realization is that this tests deterministic threshold logic, not LLM output quality. The correctness depends only on the threshold comparison, not on what the AI/ML model produces, so Agentic is disqualified.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the final structured output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9769,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9769},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1c