{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XJEmPBAWiv1KPXsmr3Uon2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SkBR5TnssCbGcSe3KpHLkC","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is wrong model configured (e.g., wrong model ID/endpoint), which returns a vector with wrong dimensions. MOCK-HIDE: A stub that returns a correctly-sized vector always passes, hiding any misconfiguration. LLM-DEP: The execution path passes through a real AI/ML embedding model call. Per LLM-DEP rules, default to Agentic when the execution path passes through a real AI/ML API call, unless the behavior EXCLUSIVELY tests infrastructure (routing, retries, payload format) with zero dependence on model output content. Dimensionality IS a property of model output, so demotion to Integration is disqualified. REJECTION-GATE: Considered System (real HTTP is sufficient since dimension is deterministic per model). Disqualifying: the rules explicitly state that passing through a real AI/ML API call defaults to Agentic, and we cannot disqualify this since we ARE testing a property of the model output (vector dimension).","test_description":"Call the real embedding service with a known query string. Assert that len(embedding_vector) equals the configured vector DB index dimension (e.g., 1536 for ada-002, 3072 for text-embedding-3-large). Run this against the actual configured embedding endpoint to verify model identity and API key/endpoint configuration are correct.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.62,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The similarity search returns results ordered by descending cosine similarity score.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in how the service layer constructs the vector DB query and parses the returned results — specifically whether it preserves or re-sorts by score. This is a module boundary failure (service ↔ vector store client). REAL-INFRA: Ordering behavior can be reproduced with an in-process fake vector store or a local embedded instance (e.g., in-memory Qdrant/Chroma) that returns pre-seeded vectors. A real external service is not required. LLM-DEP: Cosine similarity is deterministic vector math — no AI/ML model involved. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network needed — local instance suffices. (b) No AI/ML output dependency. (c/d) No agentic steps. REJECTION-GATE: Considered System (real vector DB service). Disqualifying: ordering is a property of the query execution and result parsing logic, not of real network behavior or external service idiosyncrasies. A local embedded DB instance exposes the same failure.","test_description":"Seed a local in-process vector store with N vectors at known cosine distances from a fixed query vector. Call the similarity search service method. Assert that results are sorted strictly descending by their cosine similarity score field, and that the top result corresponds to the nearest pre-seeded vector.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The LLM re-ranking step changes the order of at least some results compared to the raw similarity ranking when the query has nuanced intent.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: This behavior directly tests whether the real LLM makes contextually sensitive reordering decisions. A stub always returns a fixed permutation, so it proves nothing about whether the LLM actually re-ranks based on nuanced intent. MOCK-HIDE: Any mock or stub trivially passes — it returns 