ecision is based on cosine score thresholds, not model output quality. (c/d) No agentic chain. REJECTION-GATE: Considered Agentic (real embedding needed to generate a truly 'far' vector). Disqualifying: the behavior tests the system's response to low-score results; we can directly inject controlled low-score results into a fake vector store without invoking a real embedding model, which equally exercises the threshold filter code path.","test_description":"Seed a local in-process vector store with vectors all assigned similarity scores below the configured threshold (e.g., cosine distance > 0.8) when queried. Submit a query to the search service. Assert that the returned result list is empty. Also assert that the HTTP response body does not contain any product entries (not just that the list field is null — confirm zero items).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The end-to-end latency from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Latency measurement is meaningless with in-process fakes — stubbed calls return in microseconds and tell us nothing about real pipeline latency. We need real network round trips, real embedding API latency, real vector DB query latency, and real LLM re-ranking latency. LLM-DEP: The execution path passes through two real AI/ML API calls (embedding model + LLM re-ranker). Per LLM-DEP rules, default to Agentic when the execution path passes through a real AI/ML API call. The latency assertion is deterministic (< 2s), but the actual latency is dominated by real model inference time — a mock cannot reproduce this. MOCK-HIDE: Any mock would trivially pass the 2s threshold, completely hiding whether the real pipeline meets the SLA. REJECTION-GATE: Considered Workflow (multiple agentic steps). Disqualifying: the test does not require verifying multi-step correctness across agent decisions; it measures wall-clock time for a single request's pipeline. Workflow implies sequential agent decision chains; this is a single synchronous request through multiple services, so Agentic suffices.","test_description":"Send N=50 representative natural language queries to the live REST API endpoint (backed by real embedding model, real vector DB, and real LLM re-ranker). Record wall-clock latency for each request from HTTP request dispatch to full response receipt. Assert that the median (p50) latency is below 2000ms. Log p95 and p99 for observability. Run against a realistic-scale DB (at least 10k indexed vectors) to avoid cache-inflated results.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.68,"Workflow":0.11}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9769,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9769},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1cbeb4f3-a46a-4c4e-a8e7-a8f1a82f6839","uuid":"48d450a8-950e-4a7f-b4b0-8689d9d089f7"}
